US stocks retreated on Tuesday as Wall Street's recent sell-off resumed following two days of gains.

The S&P 500 dropped 1.1%, nearing correction territory, the Dow lost over 250 points, while the Nasdaq 100 tumbled 1.6%, pressured by weakness in technology stocks.

Tesla fell 5.5% after RBC Capital Markets cut its price target, citing growing competition in the EV market.

Alphabet shares fell 2.6%, with news showing Google will acquire cloud security Wiz for $32 billion.

Other tech names, including Nvidia and Palantir, also declined more than 2% and 3%, respectively.

Investors remain cautious ahead of the Fed's policy decision on Wednesday, with markets widely expecting interest rates to hold steady.

Attention is focused on the central bank's outlook and the potential impact of trade policy developments on market sentiment.

Meanwhile, economic data showed a stronger-than-expected rise in housing starts, while import price pressures raised concerns about inflation.

